captions.text:
Hey, you!
So it's YouTube Low-Fi week!

I decided to bust out the camera
I started making YouTube videos on

back in 2007 and make you this!
Enjoy!
Ow!
NOM NOM NOM NOM NOM NOM NOM
Ow ow ow ow ow ow ow!
Ow ow ow ow ow ow ow!

Tada!
As I said before, this is YouTube Low-Fi week!

Tada!
As I said before, this is YouTube Low-Fi week!

A week dedicated to getting rid of
all the high-production values

and just kind of showing that you
don't need a really nice camera
to make a fun video.

It's just about having fun and
doing it.

And if you look at super-high-quality content
and think

"I can't make YouTube videos because
they're never gonna look that good"

Then don't. Just start with the crappiest camera
and make the crappiest videos

and you will get better over time.
Okay? Good.
TomSka Out.

[off screen]
Jack Howard In!

[off screen]
You're in boxers!!
OH NOOOOOO--

comments.text:
+Larry Jarrins My point is that if you think they are real you have not 
handled a gun. Guns are heavy, a glock feels very heavy in the hand, a 
carbine weighs around 14Lb, and a full machine gun (like he has a MODEL of 
on the wall) weighs in the 20s. If you have ever handled a gun you would 
realize no gun owner would hang their guns one some crappy metal rack 
because they are very heavy. 

But anyways to your next claim: No, the Desert Eagle is over sized and has 
way to much recoil to be useful, it may have stopping power but you aren't 
going to get many rounds down range. If I want stoping power I will get a 
1911 which is cheaper, easier to find ammo for, more reliable, and more 
universal. The Glock is good but I fell SIG makes better, that is my 
opinion.
